    The [Ruby](https://www.ruby-lang.org/en/) programming language is perhaps best known for the [Ruby on Rails](https://rubyonrails.org/) web framework that powers sites like [Shopify](https://www.shopify.com).

    Can't wait for the next meetup? See the following resources to start learning on your own.

    ### Curriculum

    Our installfest and intro course events follow the [Railbridge tutorials](https://docs.railsbridge.org/frontend/).

    * [Installing Ruby and Rails](https://docs.railsbridge.org/installfest)
    * [Intro to Rails](https://docs.railsbridge.org/intro-to-rails)
    * [Intermediate Rails](https://docs.railsbridge.org/intermediate-rails)
    * [Frontend (HTML, CSS and JavaScript)](https://docs.railsbridge.org/frontend)

    ### Other online resources for Ruby

    * [Try Ruby](https://try.ruby-lang.org) in your browser.
    * [Rails Girls](http://railsgirls.com/materials) tutorial and tips of where to go next.
    * Play the [Ruby Warrior](https://github.com/ryanb/ruby-warrior) game by writing Ruby code.
    * Learn Ruby with the [Ruby Koans](http://rubykoans.com/).
    * Submit [exercism.io](http://exercism.io/) exercises and get feedback.

    ### Other online resources for Rails

    * [Michael Hartl's Rails tutorial](https://www.railstutorial.org/book), very popular.
    * thoughtbot has "trails" for [learning Ruby on Rails](https://thoughtbot.com/upcase/rails).

    ### Books

    * *[Learn to Program](https://pragprog.com/titles/ltp3/learn-to-program-third-edition/)*. "Chris teaches the basics, but also shows you how to think like a programmer."
    * *[Programming Ruby ("The Pickaxe")](https://pragprog.com/titles/ruby5/programming-ruby-3-3-5th-edition/)*. "This updated edition is a comprehensive reference on the language itself, with a tutorial on the most important features of Ruby—including pattern matching and Ractors—and describes the language through Ruby 3.3."
